ry vivid personal story of dancing in interwar Germany; the dance historian Marion Kant gives a systematic account of the interaction of modern dance and the totalitarian state, and a documentary appendix provides a glimpse into the twisted reality created by Nazi racism, pedantic bureaucrats and artistic ambition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aDancexPolitical aspectszGermanyxHistory. 0aModern dancezGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aNational socialism and dance. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Dance / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aKant, Marion, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKant, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarina, Lilian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteinberg, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSteinberg, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782389583?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782389583423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782389583/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK